== Yahata District == The Yahata District has a history originating from the {{ill|Government-operated Yahata Steel Works|ja|官営八幡製鐵所|12=draft|12=draft}} (Yahatahigashi-ku, Kitakyushu City, Fukuoka Prefecture). On October 1, 2012, {{ill|Nippon Steel|ja|新日本製鐵|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Sumitomo Metal Industries|ja|住友金属工業|12=draft|12=draft}}, one of the "Big Three" of the {{ill|Sumitomo Group|ja|住友グループ|12=draft|12=draft}}, merged to establish Nippon Steel & Sumitomo Metal (renamed Nippon Steel in April 2019). Kokura District traces its roots back to the {{ill|Tokyo Steel Co., Ltd. Kokura Steel Plant|ja|東京製鋼株式会社小倉製鋼所|12=draft|12=draft}}, which was completed in 1916. Before the integration, it was known as Nippon Steel & Sumitomo Metal Kokura Steelworks. On April 1, 2014, it became part of Yahata Works.<ref name="mainichi-np-2014-4-1">Munekazu Ishida (April 1, 2014). "Nippon Steel & Sumitomo Metal: New 'Yawata' is born today—Integration of two steelworks, 'Kokura' no longer remains." {{ill|Mainichi Shimbun|ja|毎日新聞|12=draft|12=draft}} (Mainichi Newspapers).</ref>
Among the assets of the Yahata Steelworks, the Former Main Office, Repair Shop, Former Forging Shop (Kitakyushu City, Fukuoka Prefecture), and the {{ill|Onga River Pump Room|ja|遠賀川水源地ポンプ室|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nakama City, Fukuoka Prefecture) are registered as components of the {{ill|Sites of Japan's Meiji Industrial Revolution: Iron and Steel, Shipbuilding, and Coal Mining|ja|明治日本の産業革命遺産 製鉄・製鋼、造船、石炭産業|12=draft|12=draft}} World Heritage Site (23 components in total).
== Overview == [[File:Higashida First Blast Furnace.JPG|thumb|right|Site of the Higashida First Blast Furnace. "1901" marks the start of operation in {{ill|1901|ja|1901st year|12=draft|12=draft}}.]] The Yahata District originated from a government-operated {{ill|steelworks|ja|製鉄所|12=draft|12=draft}} that began operations in {{ill|1901|ja|1901st year|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was Japan's second steelworks, following the {{ill|Kamaishi Mine Tanaka Steelworks|ja|釜石鉱山田中製鉄所|12=draft|12=draft}}, which had been operating since {{ill|1887|ja|1887th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meiji 20). Before {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, it was the leading domestic steelworks, producing more than half of Japan's steel. In {{ill|1934|ja|1934th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 9), the government-operated steelworks merged with private companies to establish {{ill|Nippon Steel|ja|日本製鐵|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nittetsu). After World War II, in {{ill|1950|ja|1950th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 25), Nittetsu was dismantled, and Yahata Steelworks became part of {{ill|Yawata Iron & Steel|ja|八幡製鐵|12=draft|12=draft}}. With the 1970 (Showa 45) merger of Yawata Iron & Steel and {{ill|Fuji Iron & Steel|ja|富士製鐵|12=draft|12=draft}} into {{ill|Nippon Steel Corporation|ja|新日本製鐵|12=draft|12=draft}}, the works became part of the new company.
